# Legal Defense System - Cursor AI Rules

## Project Context
This is a legal defense system built with Streamlit and Claude AI for analyzing legal documents and providing strategic legal advice.

## Code Style Guidelines
- Use Hebrew comments and docstrings for user-facing features
- English for technical/internal documentation
- Follow Python PEP 8 with 100 character line limit
- Use type hints where appropriate
- Prefer explicit over implicit code

## Architecture Principles
- main.py: Main Streamlit application
- core/: Core functionality (chatbot, AI logic)
- ui/: User interface components
- processors/: Document processing logic
- config/: Configuration and settings

## Security Rules
- NEVER hardcode API keys or secrets
- Always use .env for sensitive data
- Validate all user inputs
- Sanitize file uploads
- Log security events

## AI Integration Guidelines
- All AI prompts should include legal context
- Use professional legal language in prompts
- Always include disclaimer about AI limitations
- Provide citations for AI responses
- Handle API failures gracefully

## Legal Domain Knowledge
- Focus on civil and criminal law
- Emphasize defense strategy
- Look for contradictions and weaknesses
- Provide strategic recommendations
- Maintain professional legal terminology

## Development Workflow
- Use feature branches for new development
- Write commit messages with emoji prefixes
- Test locally before pushing
- Update CHANGELOG.md for releases
- Run secret scanning before commits

## Error Handling
- Always provide user-friendly error messages
- Log technical details for debugging
- Graceful degradation when services fail
- Clear guidance for error resolution

## Performance Guidelines
- Cache document processing results
- Optimize AI API calls
- Lazy load heavy components
- Monitor memory usage with large documents
